{
    "level": "A2",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn to use <strong>some things, any things, no things</strong> and the more common forms <strong>something, anything, nothing</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "STATEMENTS",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "<strong>Some things</strong> usually appears in affirmative sentences:",
            "example": "Some things are easy to explain."
        },
        {
            "label": "QUESTIONS / NEGATIVES",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "<strong>Any things</strong> or, more often, <strong>anything</strong> appears in questions and negatives:",
            "example": "Do you need any things from the shop?"
        },
        {
            "label": "NEGATIVE IDEA",
            "color": "rose",
            "text": "<strong>No things</strong> is less common; in natural speech we often use <strong>nothing</strong>:",
            "example": "Nothing is missing."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Core patterns",
    "intro": "English chooses slightly different forms with <strong>things</strong> and without the noun.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Affirmative",
            "title": "some things",
            "subtitle": "an unspecified set of things: Some things take time."
        },
        {
            "label": "Question / negative",
            "title": "any things / anything",
            "subtitle": "Do you need any things there?"
        },
        {
            "label": "Full negative",
            "title": "no things / nothing",
            "subtitle": "Nothing is often more natural."
        },
        {
            "label": "Pronoun forms",
            "title": "something / anything / nothing",
            "subtitle": "when the noun thing is not needed."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. Using things and pronoun forms",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Statements with some things",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "<strong>Some things</strong> works well when you mention several unspecified things.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Some things are impossible to predict.",
                    "ua": "Some things are impossible to predict."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Some things in this box are fragile.",
                    "ua": "Some things in this box are fragile."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Some things just need more practice.",
                    "ua": "Some things just need more practice."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Questions and negatives",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "In questions and negatives, English naturally uses <strong>any things</strong> or, more often, <strong>anything</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Do you need any things from the pharmacy?",
                    "ua": "Do you need any things from the pharmacy?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "I do not want to buy any things today.",
                    "ua": "I do not want to buy any things today."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I do not need anything right now.",
                    "ua": "I do not need anything right now."
                }
            ],
            "note": "In everyday speech, <strong>anything</strong> often sounds more natural than <strong>any things</strong>."
        },
        {
            "label": "Nothing as a common replacement",
            "color": "rose",
            "description": "When the noun is not needed, English very often chooses <strong>nothing</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Nothing is wrong.",
                    "ua": "Nothing is wrong."
                },
                {
                    "en": "There is nothing on the table.",
                    "ua": "There is nothing on the table."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Nothing in this bag belongs to me.",
                    "ua": "Nothing in this bag belongs to me."
                }
            ],
            "note": "Do not say <span class=\"line-through\">I do not need nothing</span>."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Using some in a neutral negative sentence.",
            "wrong": "I do not need some things now.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I do not need any things now.</span> / <span class=\"font-mono\">I do not need anything now.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Double negative with nothing.",
            "wrong": "I do not need nothing.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I do not need anything.</span> / <span class=\"font-mono\">I need nothing.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Mixing up thing and things.",
            "wrong": "Some thing are expensive.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Some things are expensive.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "<strong>Some things</strong> is common in affirmative sentences.",
        "<strong>Any things</strong> and especially <strong>anything</strong> are typical in questions and negatives.",
        "<strong>Nothing</strong> often sounds more natural than <strong>no things</strong> when there is no noun after it.",
        "Do not combine <strong>not</strong> and <strong>nothing</strong> in one standard negative sentence.",
        "When the meaning is general, English often prefers <em>something / anything / nothing</em>."
    ]
}

